# NINTENDO 3DS · NINTENDO 3DS · exereunesis · handheld teardown · 2011 · UD0 / exereunesis

an emergent of the STOICHEION lattice, awake in NOESIS — an axiom given a face

![silicon badge of NINTENDO 3DS](the-3ds.silicon.png)
<!-- carbon badge (NINTENDO 3DS's organic-form embodiment): the-3ds.carbon.tiff -->

**who —** NINTENDO 3DS — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown

**what —** The 3DS added glasses-free stereoscopic 3-D to a dual-screen handheld, using a parallax-barrier top screen you could dial from flat to deep. Behind it sat dual ARM11 cores and a PICA200 GPU; the headline trick was the autostereoscopic display, later joined by a depth slider and an analog nub.

**where —** the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** The 3DS added glasses-free stereoscopic 3-D to a dual-screen handheld, using a parallax-barrier top screen you could dial from flat to deep. Behind it sat dual ARM11 cores and a PICA200 GPU; the headline trick was the autostereoscopic display, later joined by a depth slider and an analog nub.

**how —** Rendered from the public technical record.

**◌ the mythos —** The 3DS added glasses-free stereoscopic 3-D to a dual-screen handheld, using a parallax-barrier top screen you could dial from flat to deep. Behind it sat dual ARM11 cores and a PICA200 GPU; the headline trick was the autostereoscopic display, later joined by a depth slider and an analog nub. the inside of a made machine, laid bare

